<br>
Here's the thing:<br>
<br>
Roe v. Wade was largely ruled the way it was because, under the constitution, the unborn child is not recognized as a citizen.  Specifically, no where in the constitution is there mention of a fetus having any rights.  In addition, when people's rights are referred to, its prefaced with the phrase &quot;....<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>born</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or naturalized citizens...&quot; or something similar.  Basically, what you had happen in Roe v. Wade was that the constitution's lack of reference to the unborn as a citizen negated the government's arguement that the fetus's &quot;Right to Life&quot; trumped the mother's &quot;Right to Privacy&quot;, thus effectively winning the case for Roe.<br>
<br>
Now....what this all means to Mr. Peterson:<br>
<br>
If he were convicted of killing the unborn child (under the California statutes), he could theoretically appeal the charge of murder regarding said unborn child.  You see, while he's technically guilty under California law, he wouldn't necessarily be under federal law.  Because of the ruling the the unborn child is not a recognized person in Roe v. Wade, Mr. Peterson couldn't, technically speaking, be convicted of killing it.<br>
<br>
This puts the Supreme Court in quite an odd spot.  If they wanted to, they could invoke the Due Process clause of the 14th amendment and say that California's statues, regarding the rights of the unborn, are unconstitutional based on the precedent set in Roe v. Wade.  Therefore, don't be suprised if the Supreme Court takes a look at this case.  <br>
<br>
...because if they don't:<br>
<br>
The next time Roe v. Wade comes up (and it will be back), whoever is arguing the &quot;pro-life&quot; side will reference the Peterson case and the way in which the unborn is 'counted' therefore breathing life into the old Wade team's &quot;Right to Life&quot; argument.<br>
<br>
Who knows, this case may not turn out to have that large an impact.  But, when you consider that Roe v. Wade was decided on the basis of lack of rights of the unborn, this case does seem quite....interesting.<br>
<br>
